english:
  title: Preface to the Recorded Sayings of Daego
  author: Lee Sunggin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Learning requires the proper lineage of teachers and friends to be transmissible. So it is even among the Buddhist teachings. When the Buddha passed, Kasyapa received his doctrine and transmitted it through an unbroken succession until it reached Bodhidharma, who entered the Middle Kingdom. Thereafter, the Great Mirror transmitted it through one or two generations, after which it branched into five schools: the Great Circle became Guiyang, Huizhao became Linji, Kuangzhen became Yunmen, Zhicang became Fayan, and Wuji became Caodong. Yet it was only the teaching of Huizhao that flourished. In these times, all who speak of Chan Buddhism say but one thing: "We are Linji." Surely this is the height of prosperity. According to the records of the Buddhist monk Daoyuan of Wu, there are some seventeen hundred lineages recorded, among which our Eastern people are counted, their teachers and lineages evident for all to trace.

    In recent times, Daego was a man of uncommon spirit. Taking up a single staff, he wandered the rivers and lakes until he came to Xiawu Mountain in Wuxing, where he encountered Master Shiwu Zhu. Through direct encounter he grasped the subtle meaning. Upon his departure, Shiwu transmitted to him the monastic robes—thus transmitting the Dharma mind itself. Shiwu was the true-line descendant of Linji in the eighteenth generation, and through Daego this lineage became established as a great school.

    When Daego returned to his homeland, our King Gongmin received him with the utmost reverence and propriety. Yet Daego dwelt as though untouched by such honor, and within mere months he vanished. Later it was learned he had returned to his former hermitage. There he built a small dwelling on Little Snow Mountain, sustained himself on simple gruel and vegetables, lived in quiet restraint, and received few visitors. One evening he passed into stillness, and the strange relics that appeared were indeed enough to astonish the world.

    Now Master Wang, the elder Guchuang, was his foremost disciple. He has gathered what was heard at the teaching seat and compiled these volumes, titling them the Recorded Sayings of Daego, asking me to write this preface. As for Daego's teaching, I dare not claim to understand it. Brief phrases and scattered passages—I have not had leisure to examine their meaning. Yet the very correctness of his lineage alone provides a model for his followers, and his conduct from beginning to end admits of no fault when measured against the Way. Thus I write this at the head of his volume and send it forth. Ah, what need has this record of my words for its transmission to the world? What need indeed?
  footnotes:
    - 'Linji (臨濟): One of the five major schools of Chan Buddhism, which became historically dominant in East Asia, including Korea and Japan.'
    - 'Shiwu Zhu (石屋珙): An important Chan master of the Yuan Dynasty, here identified as the eighteenth-generation descendant in the Linji lineage.'
    - The reference to Daego's miraculous relics (舍利) upon his death reflects a traditional Buddhist understanding of enlightened masters leaving behind crystalline remains as evidence of spiritual achievement.
    - 'King Gongmin: The ruler of Goryeo during the time of this preface, showing the close relationship between Daego and the royal court.'
